To generate a random string with a length of 10 in .NET Core, you can use the `System.Random` class along with a combination of characters from which the string can be composed. Here's an example code snippet:

```csharp
using System;

public class RandomStringGenerator
{
    private static readonly Random random = new Random();

    public static string GenerateRandomString(int length)
    {
        const string chars = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789";
        return new string(Enumerable.Repeat(chars, length)
          .Select(s => s[random.Next(s.Length)]).ToArray());
    }
}
```

You can then use the `GenerateRandomString` method to generate a random string with a specified length. For example:

```csharp
string randomString = RandomStringGenerator.GenerateRandomString(10);
Console.WriteLine(randomString);
```

Each time you run the code, it will generate a different random string with a length of 10 characters. The string can contain uppercase and lowercase letters, as well as digits from 0 to 9.
